{Partner bids Stayman; with no 4-card Major you respond 2\D. Partner now bids 3\S.   

Partner bids Stayman; with no 4-card Major you respond 2\D. Partner now bids 3\S.   

Partner's bidding is crystal clear. He has described a hand with at least 11 points, which has 4 \Hs and 5 \Ss.

The decision is yours, and with no 8-card Major suit fit you decide on 3NT.

East plays 3NT. On South's \HJ opening lead North plays the \HQ.

On South's \HJ opening lead North plays the \HQ.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 2 : \D = 3 : \C = 2 :: Total = 7

You must establish some \S tricks which means you will be finessing through South. Since South can get the lead at most once in \Ss you should not hold up in \Hs. The problem with a hold up is that North may pocket one \H trick and then switch to \Cs, a suit in which you are no better off. 

Win the \HK and play your \S9, letting it ride. Suppose it holds the trick. Continue with another \S, taken by North's \SQ. 

North cannot hurt you. If he has a \H to play, then \Hs will have broken no worse than 4-2 and you will lose two \Hs and two \Ss.

If North plays any other suit you have a double stopper and can establish \S tricks before they can set up a winner of their own.

Suppose you let North hold the \HQ. That's one trick for the bad guys.

North could play a \C, knocking out one of your \C A K. When North won his first \S he would establish the \Cs, and when he took the second \S he could cash 2 \C tricks. }
[Play "W"]HJ

