{Partner's 1NT overcall shows 15-18 points and guarantees a \S stop. With 11 points and no 4-card \H suit you say 3NT.

The contract would be 3NT played by East.

West plays 3NT. North leads the \SK. Do you hold up or not?

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 3 : \D = 2 : \C = 2 :: Total = 8

You need just one more winner. It could come from a finesse of the \CJ. It could come from a 3-3 \H split. It could come by establishing a fourth card in \Ds.

Most important for now is the \S lead? Do you hold up? 

Yes you should hold up. In fact you might as well hold up twice since you aren't contemplating a throw-in of North. Holding up twice will protect you in the unlikely event that North made his 2\S bid with a 5-card suit. 

Both the \H possibility and the \C possibility will either work or not, so you can save them for later. Your highest percentage chance is the fourth \D, but here you must be careful. You must try to establish the \Ds without allowing North to get the lead. It is actually pretty easy. Just play a small \D from your hand and when North plays low insert the \D10. South wins the \DJ but cannot harm you with his return.

When the remaining \Ds fall you have established your ninth trick.

Suppose North inkles out what you are trying to do and inserts his \DQ when you play the low \D toward dummy? 

If he does that he hands you all four \D tricks!}
[Play "W"]SK

